# Tooling, Versioning, And Automation

- RULE: Use the pinned .NET 11 Preview 3 SDK, C# preview mode, Node.js 25, and pnpm as the repository toolchain baseline.
- RULE: Use pnpm, not npm, for repository tooling installs and script execution.
- RULE: Treat `tools/` implementations as local-only drops. Track only
  `tools/README.md` and each direct tool directory's `README.md` unless ADR
  accepts a tool implementation into the repository.
- RULE: Preview language features may be adopted only when the pinned SDK compiles them in a normal repository build without unsupported shims.
- RULE: Do not use C# `union` declarations in product code until the pinned SDK and runtime provide a complete repository-ready path.
- RULE: Keep `.editorconfig` companion analyzer and analysis-mode properties
  explicit in `Directory.Build.props` rather than relying on SDK defaults.
- RULE: The analyzer severity doctrine is binary: error by default, none only
  for path-scoped exceptions.
- RULE: Reserve future repository analyzer IDs only when ADR documents the
  activation condition and the current build remains stable without the
  analyzer package present.
- RULE: Keep Conventional Commits and CalVer `vYY.MM.PATCH`.
- RULE: Release automation must use the explicit project `Version` property as
  the release tag source, including deliberate out-of-month CalVer bumps.
- RULE: Local pre-push is the full-fidelity validation lane. Remote CI may run
  only the light test lane when the heavier checks remain enforced locally.
- RULE: Local validation must generate
  `artifacts/coverage/coverage.xml` and report coverage without a minimum
  percentage gate.
- RULE: Editor-facing coverage tooling must read the canonical
  `artifacts/coverage/coverage.xml` artifact instead of ad hoc coverage paths.
- RULE: Generated code, native shell glue, DI bootstrap files, and OS-bound
  runtime orchestration without deterministic unit seams must stay out of the
  coverage denominator and be validated by the heavy local lane instead.
- RULE: Source-only repository lint is the enforcement path for forbidden constructs that analyzers cannot scope away from generated code.
- RULE: Release automation belongs to successful pushes to `main` and must remain derived from commit history.
- RULE: `CHANGELOG.md` must keep an `Unreleased` section between release tags, and release notes must derive from the tagged changelog section.
- RULE: Non-deliverable pushes may skip release publication only through the explicit `[skip release]` marker.
- RULE: Release assets and update logic must target one self-contained delivery.
- RULE: The Windows release lane publishes one self-contained Native AOT executable.
- RULE: The local heavy lane must include a Native AOT self-contained publish
  smoke plus an updater rehearsal for legacy-layout migration and automatic
  relaunch.
